06136nam a22009855i 9783110661774DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106617747 a10.1515/97831106617742doi  a(DE-B1597)522274  a(OCoLC)1114819441  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0020002bisacsh00aMedicine and Paradoxography in the Ancient World /ced. by George Kazantzidis. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VIII, 225 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ;v8100tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Medicine and Paradoxography in Dialogue -- tTechnological Wonder in Herodotus’ Histories -- tParadoxography and the pseudo- Aristotelian Problemata -- tIn the Realm of the Two-Headed Snake -- tWondrous Healings in Greek Epigrams (and Their Parodic Counterparts) -- tBeyond the Limits of the Human Body -- tPhlegon’s Paradoxical Physiology -- tGalen’s Language of Wonder -- tLiterary Remedies and Rhetorical Prescriptions in Aelius Aristides -- tUnknowable Questions and Paradoxography in ps.–Alexander of Aphrodisias’ Medical Puzzles and Natural Problems -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex Rerum et Nominum -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe present volume offers a systematic discussion of the complex relationship between medicine and paradoxography in the ancient world.For a long time, the relationship between the two has been assumed to be virtually non-existent. Paradoxography is concerned with disclosing a world full of marvels and wondrous occurrences without providing an answer as to how these phenomena can be explained. Its main aim is to astonish and leave its readers bewildered and confused. By contrast, medicine is committed to the rational explanation of human phusis, which makes it, in a number of significant ways, incompatible with thauma. This volume moves beyond the binary opposition between ‘rational’ and ‘non-rational’ modes of thinking, by focusing on instances in which the paradox is construed with direct reference to established medical sources and beliefs or, inversely, on cases in which medical discourse allows space for wonder and admiration. Its aim is to show that thauma, rather than present a barrier, functions as a concept which effectively allows for the dialogue between medicine and paradoxography in the ancient world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aGriechische Literatur. 0aMedicine. 0aMedizin der Antike. 0aParadoxographie. 0aparadoxography. 0athauma. 4aGriechische Literatur. 4aMedizin der Antike. 4aParadoxographie. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  amedicine.  aparadoxography.  athauma.1 aDoroszewska, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFloridi, Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerolemou, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazantzidis, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazantzidis, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLightfoot, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeeusen, Michiel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOikonomopoulou, Katerina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOverduin, Floris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetridou, Georgia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShannon-Henderson, Kelly E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator